node.text: Olympic diver Jordan Windle is making his dad, who adopted him from Cambodia at 18 months old, proud at #Tokyo2020. Jerry, who is gay, had "wanted to be a dad for as long as I could remember," he has said. Jordan, who took up diving by chance at a summer camp when he was 7 years old and who went on to be the youngest diver to make it to the Olympic trials is now, at 22, competing for Team USA. "I tell everyone, when they ask me why I dive, I dive purely for my dad and how much he loves watching me," Jordan said. "Without him making all the sacrifices that he has, and his love and support the whole time we've been together, I really wouldn't be where I am today." ❤️ Tap the link in bio for the beautiful full story. #Regram @jordanpiseywindle

node.text: Allyson Felix is capping off her fifth and final games as the most decorated Olympic track athlete, man or woman, in U.S. history. 🙌 On Saturday, the 15th day of the Tokyo Games, Felix, 35, won gold in the final race of her career with relay teammates Sydney McLaughlin, Dalilah Muhammad and Athing Mu. "I have so much respect and admiration and I know I would not have been here without those who paved the way," the mom of one said. "I am grateful for my own journey, I love the sport and it is very special to be 35 and still doing what I love." ❤️ |📷: David Ramos/Getty

node.text:
Tamyra Mensah-Stock's Olympic victory is more than just a win for herself. 🙌  The Team USA athlete, who become the first Black woman to win an Olympic gold medal in wrestling for America earlier this week, says she plans to use the gold medal winnings to help make her mom's dreams come true. 

In support of her mom's passion for cooking, Mensah-Stock says she's purchasing a food truck she'll name "The Lady Bug" so that her mom can sell her cooking from wherever she wants. "I made a promise to her and she loves cooking," Mensah-Stock explains of the food truck plans. "It's just one of her passions. ❤️

Tap the bio link for the full story. |📷: Tom Pennington/Getty Images
